  "bib_entries": {
    "38668184": {
      "title": "Pathogenesis of pneumococcal pneumonia",
      "abstract": "Pneumococcal pneumonia poses a serious threat to children in developing countries and remains an important disease in the industrialized world. Capsular polysaccharide is the only bacterial factor proven to contribute to pathogenesis. However, the mechanisms responsible for the hypoxemia, toxemia, crisis, and death associated with this common infection are poorly understood. Toxins secreted by the bacteria, byproducts of bacterial breakdown (e.g., pneumolysin or teichoic acid), or constituents of the intense inflammatory response in the lung might play a role in these phenomena"
    }
